well? "Yes, thank Heaven," replied he:
"but my &s;i&s;ter"&mdash;"what, Mrs. Elphin|&s;tone?"
"no my other&mdash;my unfortunate
&s;i&s;ter Emily&mdash;I have been &s;ent for to her at
Bri&s;tol, where, you know I went to her &s;ome
time &s;ince, at your entreaty: &s;he has now, I
think, only a few days to live&mdash;my &s;i&s;ter
Elphin&s;tone is with her&mdash;poor Emily wi&s;hes
to &s;ee you&mdash;I know not how to a&s;k &s;uch a fa|vour
of you; but you are <HI>&s;o</HI> good&mdash;will you&mdash;can
you oblige a family&mdash;who already owe
to you all the happine&s;s they po&s;&s;e&s;s?"</P>
<P>"What will I not do to give any part of
it &s;atisfaction," &s;aid Cele&s;tina&mdash;"but do you,
can you gue&s;s the rea&s;on of your &s;i&s;ter's wi&s;hes
<PB N="303" REF="305">
to &s;ee me? &s;urely Vava&s;our is not there?&mdash;"He
was not, when I left her; but a few
days before, he had been at Bri&s;tol, raving
like a madman at the fatal intelligence he had
