melancholy.</P>
<P>The anxious peer, who&s;e health was, as
u&s;ual, a little amended by change of country,
waited at Paris the promi&s;ed arrival of Wil|loughby,
with extreme impatience: impatience
which had &s;uch an effect upon his feeble frame,
that death, which had &s;o long been laying in
wait for him, now &s;eized him, and at a period,
when the blow &s;aved him from knowing what
<PB N="314" REF="316">
could not have been concealed from him many
