Lady Ca&s;tlenorth would be but
faintly de&s;cribed by the &s;tronge&s;t of tho&s;e re|pre&s;entations
that have been given of an en|raged
woman, when &s;he has been compared
to a tygre&s;s robbed of her young.&mdash;Cava|naugh
had po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed the art to make her be|lieve,
that his admiration of her mental per|fections
was the foundation of that attach|ment
he felt for her; yet, that while he ador|ed
her beautiful mind, her fine per&s;on was an
object of tender admiration. To find that he
cared for neither the one nor the other; but
