great acqui&s;itions, the price of &s;o much pa|tient
perfidy.&mdash;Though he would willingly
have been excu&s;ed giving to Willoughby even
the &s;mall &s;hare of the ample property which
his uncle had a&s;&s;igned to him; yet he knew
he mu&s;t &s;ee the will, and finally obtain it. He
thought it better, therefore, to continue with
him the appearance of honour; and therefore
wrote to him, informing him of Lord Ca&s;tle|north's
death; of his own marriage; and the
<PB N="317" REF="319">
codicil in favour of Mr. Willoughby. But
not knowing whither to direct this letter; for
Willoughby had left no intimation of the
route he meant to pur&s;ue, when he quitted
Paris; he addre&s;&s;ed it to Alve&s;tone; where,
with one on the &s;ame bu&s;ine&s;s from Lady
Ca&s;tlenorth, it lay, while Willoughby was
wandering among the Pyrenian mountains,
and while he pur&s;ued his impatient way to|wards
